<h1>@HI{{naku}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Aistem{{}}@HI{{ku@EM{{naku}}}}
<li> @Anastem@HI{{deha@EM{{naku}}}}
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{deha@EM{{naku}}}}
<li> @V{{}}@HI{{ku@EM{{naku}}naru}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{naku}}}} is the continuative form of @HI{{nai}}, used in written Japanese.
<a href="grammar-nakute.html">@HI{{nakute}}</a>, on the other hand, can be used in both spoken and written Japanese.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When attached to an @HI{{i}}-adjective or @HI{{na}}-adjective, @HI{{@EM{{naku}}}} indicates a reason or a cause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^book^word}}no@FG{{@KJ{{period^extremity}}:kimatsu}}@FG{{@KJ{{test^verification}}:shiken'}}haamari@KJ{{difficult}}shiku@EM{{naku}},hottoshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The Japanese final examination was not very hard and I felt relieved.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
<p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When attached to a noun @HI{{@EM{{naku}}}} indicates a contrast.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}no@FG{{@KJ{{polish^research}}:kenkyuu}}@FG{{@KJ{{vis-a-vis^elephant}}:taishou}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{present^substitute^history}}:gendaishi}}deha@EM{{naku}},
      @FG{{@KJ{{old^substitute^history}}:kodaishi}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      My research area is not modern history but ancient history.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
However, if the noun is a Sino-Japanese one with an adjectival nature, then it indicates a reason for what follows.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{write}}ita@KJ{{book}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{fond^evaluate}}:kouhyou}}de@EM{{naku}},gakkarishita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The book I wrote was not popular, and I felt disappointed.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
A verb cannot precede @HI{{@EM{{naku}}}} unless it is followed by the verb @HI{{naru}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{uchino@KJ{{child}}ha@KJ{{book}}wo@KJ{{read}}ma@EM{{naku}}narimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Our child doesn't read books any more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a href="grammar-nakute.html">@HI{{nakute}}</a> does not have this restriction.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{uchino@KJ{{child}}ha@KJ{{book}}wo@KJ{{read}}manakute,@FG{{@KJ{{quandary}}:koma}}rundesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Our child doesn't read books and we don't know what to do.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{naku}}}} only modifies adjectives with positive meanings.
</p>

<p>
Only nouns that incorporate the idea of an adjective or adverb can be modified by @HI{{@EM{{naku}}}}.
</p>

